        "name": "Generic grass, hay",
        "termType": "crop",
        "@id": "genericGrassHay",
        "units": "kg"
      },
      "value": [
        79078
      ],
      "isAnimalFeed": true,
      "methodClassification": "modelled",
      "methodClassificationDescription": "Consumption of grassland-derived feedstuffs was only roughly known, because of year-to-year variability and lack of available data in farms with a traditional feeding system based on hay consumption ad-libitum. \nSo, we recorded the total permanent farm agricultural area (perm_FAA), its proportion destined to each crop, and the types and quantities of fertilizers (organic and chemical) in order to estimate the grassland production. We estimated the grassland production (GRASSLAND_model) on the basis of the area and of N fertilization rate (Scotton et al., 2005). Afterwards, we compared GRASSLAND_model with the feed intake calculation (i.e., the sum of hay, grass silage and grass at pasture amounts as obtained from feed rations and animal NE requirements, GRASSLAND_intake), subtracted the field losses (losses factors derived from Bretscher, 2010), assuming that GRASSLAND_intake amount was covered by the GRASSLAND_model. When a deficit was found, we implicitly assumed that a deficit-correspondent amount of hay (first marginal feedstuff) and secondly of grass silage (second marginal feedstuff) were purchased.",
      "min": [
        0
      ],
      "max": [
        192508
      ],
      "sd": [
        1212
      ],
      "statsDefinition": "sites",
      "properties": [
